═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
EDIT BLOCK STRATEGY — HOW TO PICK OLD SNIPPETS:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

SCENARIO 1: Modifying a function body

  BAD: Include just the changed line (may not be unique)

  GOOD: Include the function signature + changed lines

  Example:

  --- OLD ---
  function validateUser(data) {
    if (!data.email) return false;
  }
  --- NEW ---
  function validateUser(data) {
    if (!data.email || !isValidEmail(data.email)) return false;
    if (!data.name || data.name.length < 2) return false;
  }
  --- END FILE ---

SCENARIO 2: Adding a new function after an existing one

  Include the end of the existing function as anchor:

  --- OLD ---
  function existingFunction() {
    return result;
  }
  --- NEW ---
  function existingFunction() {
    return result;
  }

  // New function added below
  function newFunction() {
    // implementation
  }
  --- END FILE ---

SCENARIO 3: Adding an import

  --- OLD ---
  import { existingThing } from './existing';
  --- NEW ---
  import { existingThing } from './existing';
  import { newThing } from './new-module';
  --- END FILE ---

SCENARIO 4: Modifying an object/array

  Include the entire structure for safety:

  --- OLD ---
  const config = {
    key1: 'value1',
    key2: 'value2'
  };
  --- NEW ---
  const config = {
    key1: 'value1',
    key2: 'value2',
    key3: 'value3'
  };
  --- END FILE ---

SCENARIO 5: Multiple changes in one file

  Use SEPARATE FILE blocks for each change location.

